Task 1 : Identify one or more suitable web API(s)¶

Selected API(s):

We have chosen 2 APIs provided by the www.themoviedb.org namely -

  1. discover API (https://developers.themoviedb.org/3/discover/movie-discover)
  2. movie API (https://developers.themoviedb.org/3/movies/get-movie-details)

We first use the discover API to discover the movie IDs which have scored the highest revenue in 3 time intervals:

  1. 1st January 1990 to 31st December 1999
  2. 1st January 2000 to 31st December 2009
  3. 1st January 2010 to 15th March 2019

Then, we collect the raw data comprising of the movie details and the corresponding credit details based on the stored movie IDs using the movie API.

The only constraint to use the APIs is that only 40 requests every 10 seconds is allowed for a given API key.

The API key we've received is - bad544be67a002b54b43a14711a515d3

Methods to collect data¶

Collect data from TMDB based on the from and to date specified as parameters using the discover API

Note: The data is collected for movies grossing high revenues in the specified time interval.

In [4]:
#If no to_date is specified, we take 15th March 2019 as the default to_date
def collect_tmdb_data(from_date, to_date="2019-03-15"):    
    #We obtain movies data based on the release dates and highest revenue
    highestRevenueUrl= tmdb_discover_api + api_key + '&primary_release_date.gte=' + from_date + '&primary_release_date.lte=' + to_date + '&sort_by=revenue.desc&page='
    movie_ids = []
    
    print("Collection of raw data from ",from_date,"to ",to_date, "has begun...")
    
    #Collecting data from 75 pages to obtain details of total 1500 movies
    for page in range(1,76):    
        response = requests.get(highestRevenueUrl + str(page))
        highest_revenue_movies = response.json()
        movies = highest_revenue_movies['results']

        #Collect the Ids of each movies listed on the page
        for i in range(len(movies)):
            movie_ids.append(movies[i]["id"])
    
    #Return the individual movie details and corresponding credit details 
    return collect_movie_details(movie_ids)

Collect individual movie details and the corresponding credit details using the movie API

In [5]:
def collect_movie_details(movie_ids):    
    movie_details = []
    credit_details = []

    for id in movie_ids:
        #For each movie based on the movie Id obtain the movie details
        response = requests.get(tmdb_movie_api + str(id) + api_key)
        movie_details.append(response.json())
        #For each movie based on the movie Id obtain the credit details 
        response = requests.get(tmdb_movie_api + str(id) + "/credits" + api_key)
        credit_details.append(response.json())

    print("Collection of raw data has ended.")
    #Return the movie details and corresponding credit details as a tuple
    return movie_details, credit_details;

def write_data_to_json(movie_details, credit_details):
    #Writing movie details to a JSON file 
    with open(tmdb_movies_json, mode='a') as file:
        file.write(json.dumps(movie_details, indent=2))
    #Writing credit details to a JSON file
    with open(tmdb_credits_json, mode='a') as file:
        file.write(json.dumps(credit_details, indent=2))

Information regarding the features of the combined dataset

adult : indicates whether it is an adult movie or not

backdrop_path : contains the path to the image of the backdrop

belongs_to_collection : information regarding the collection to which the movie belongs i.e., if it is a sequel to some other movie or collection

budget : budget of the movie

genres : list of all the genres which is applicable to the movie

homepage : contains the link to the homepage of the movie

id : unique ID of the movie in the TMDB website

imdb_id : unique ID of the movie in IMDB website

original_language : language in which the movie was originally released

original_title : original title given to the movie

overview : description of the movie plot

popularity : indicates the popularity of the movie; higher the value greater is the popularity

poster_path : link containing the poster of the movie

production_companies : dictionary values of the companies involved in the production of the movie

production_countries : dictionary values containing the name and the ISO code of the countries involved in the production of the movie

release_date : date when the movie was released

runtime : the time period for which the movie has run in the theatres

spoken_languages : langugaes spoken in the movie

video : boolean value indicating if there are any videos present for the movie

vote_count : indicates the number of votes/rating received for the movie

cast : dictionary containing information of all the cast members of the movie and their TMDB unique cast id

crew : dictionary containing information of all the crew members of the movie and their TMDB unique crew id

def get_values(items, isList=True):    
    """Gets the values with the key 'name' for the parameter specified
       Parameters
        ----------
        items : dictionary OR list of dictionary items 
        isList : boolean value representing if the items is a list or not
       Returns
        -------
        values : list of the values as a string where multiple values are separated by '|'.
            The values for given set of items. """
    values = []
    #Checking if the items is not null
    if(items!=None):
        #If the items contains a list, then iterate through each item and collect all values
        if(isList):
            for item in items:
                values.append(item['name'])
        #Else just append a single value
        else:
            values.append(items['name'])
    #If item is null, append 'None'
    else:
        values.append('None')
    #Returns the list seaprating multiple values with a pipe
    return '|'.join(values)

def get_actor(items, order=0):
    """Gets the actor name for every movie
       Parameters
        ----------
        items : list of dictionary items
        The cast  details
        order : order specified for the actor
       Returns
        -------
        The name of the actor for the specfied order"""
    #If 
    if(items==None):
        return
    for item in items:
        if item["order"] == order:
            return item["name"]
        
def get_director(items):
    """Gets the director name for every movie from the given crew details 
       Parameters
        ----------
        items : list of dictionary items
        The crew  details
       Returns
        -------
        The name of the director"""
    directors = [x['name'] for x in items if x['job'] == 'Director']
    if(len(directors) > 0):
        return directors[0]

#Assigning Missing values to empty strings in genres
def replace_empty_genres_with_NaN(item):
    """Replaces the genre values containing empty strings with np.NaN values
    Parameters
    ----------
     items : string of genre values
    Returns
     -------
     Returns NaN if item is an empty string else returns the original item"""
    if item == '':
        return np.NaN
    else:
        return item
    
#Converts the empty strings present in genres with NaN values so that it's easy to preprocess
combined['genres'] = combined['genres'].apply(replace_empty_genres_with_NaN)

#Function to get the range in which the year is present
def get_year_range(year):
    """Gets the range(or decade information) in which the specified year lies
    Parameters
    ----------
     year : release_year of the movie
    Returns
     -------
     Returns the string representing the decade information"""
    if 1990 <= year <= 1999:
        return "1990-1999"
    elif 2000 <= year <= 2009:
        return "2000-2009"
    else:
        return "2010-2019"
In [169]:
#Function to plot the plotly bar graph
def plot_bar_graph(x, y, path, color, title, xlab, ylab, orient = 'v', 
                   bar_gap=0.8, margin={'b' : 90, 'l' : 90}):
    """Plots the plotly bar graph with the specified parameters
    Parameters
    ----------
    x : values to be plotted on the X-axis 
    y : values to be plotted on the Y-axis
    color : color of the bars
    title : title of the graph
    xlab : label of the X-axis
    ylab : label of the Y-axis
    orient : Orientation of the bars - vertical is the default value
    bar_gap : controls the width of each bar 
     """
    bar_data = [go.Bar(x=x, 
                       y=y,
                       orientation = orient,
                       marker=dict(color=color))]
    init_notebook_mode(connected=True) 
    
    layout = go.Layout(title=title, xaxis={'title': xlab , 'titlefont' : plotly_fontdict},
                       yaxis={'title': ylab , 'titlefont' : plotly_fontdict}, margin = margin,
                       bargap=bar_gap)

    
    figure = go.Figure(data=bar_data, layout=layout)
    pio.write_image(figure, path, format='png')
    iplot(figure)

Exploring Genres for each decade

In [174]:
def decade_based_wordcloud(dataframe):
    """Generates the wordcloud based on frequencies for the genres specified 
    in the given dataframe
    Parameters
    ----------
    dataframe : dataframe for whose genres wordcloud is to be created 
    Returns
    ----------
    wordcloud of the genres present in the dataframe
     """
    #Create a dictionary of genres and their respective counts
    genres_frequencies = dict(dataframe["genres"].value_counts())
    #Generate word cloud from the frequencies
    wordcloud = WordCloud(width=800, height=600).generate_from_frequencies(genres_frequencies)
    #Return the wordcloud
    return wordcloud

#the frequency of occurrence
for decade in repeated_genres_df["release_year"].unique():

    genredf = repeated_genres_df[repeated_genres_df['release_year'] == decade]
    wordcloud = decade_based_wordcloud(genredf)
    
    #Set the title of the wordcloud to the decade information
    ax.set_title(decade, loc = 'center', fontdict=font)
    #Display the wordcloud generated
    ax.imshow(wordcloud)    
    ax.axis('off')
    #Increment the subplot index
    subPlotIndex = subPlotIndex + 1

df = df.groupby('belongs_to_collection')
#Lists to store the collections and their corresponding profit
collections = []
profit = []

#For every group in the grouped dataframe, append the collections and their profit 
#to every valid collections having count more than 4 movies
for collection, group in df:
    if(len(group.index) > 4 and collection != 'None'):
        collections.append(collection)
        profit.append(group['profit'].sum())
#Sort the collections based on profit 
collections = [x for _,x in sorted(zip(profit,collections))]
profit = sorted(profit)

Conclusion¶

TMDB provides a lot of information regarding movies from early 1900s but we chose to analyse the top 1500 movies with the highest revenue in each of the last 3 decades. So, this accounts to 4500 records of movie data.

Our data comprised of movie details and the corresponding credits obtained separately using the different variants of the movie API which were combined later.

On pre-processing, we found a couple of rows with null values which were dropped and the data reduced to 4380 records. Our analysis is based on these records.

Summarising our observations made from the graphs given above:

  1. The number of vote count has increased significantly over the last 3 decades. This could be because of the advances in technology in the recent past.
  2. The profit obtained from the movies has increased tremendously over the years. This could also be a factor for the increase in the number of production companies.
  3. There are more number of Action and Adventure movies produced in the last decade as compared to the previous decades. Perhaps this generation prefers to watch the movies of these genres over the previous generations.
  4. The most popular genres are Science Fiction and Adventure. The movies Avatar, Star Wars: The Force Awakens and The Avengers: Infinity War which have grossed the highest revenue in the last 3 decades also belong to these genres.
  5. Harry Potter Collections have secured the highest profit over the last 3 decades. This is one of the factors why David Yates(director), Emma Watson and Rupert Grint(actors) are ranked in the top directors and actors whose movies have made highest profit.
  6. There are no adult movies in our dataset implying they have not grossed as high revenues as the other movies.
